items.title: Genduara subnotata
items.content_text: This moth easily loses its scales on the wings which gives them the appearance of  being clear.

items.title: Proteuxoa sanguinipuncta
items.content_text: A largish moth with stunning colours.  Loves to sit with head beneath something like a blade of grass(can't see you so you can't see me).

items.title: Syringoseca rhodoxantha
items.content_text: This moth is in the Oecophoridae family.

items.title: Entometa fervens
items.content_text: This beautiful moth is one of the larger moths and eventually sits still long enough for a photo.

items.title: Ectopatria horologa
items.content_text: Not common but has been seen in Bacchus Marsh and Long forest previously.  It has a kidney-shaped white spot on each forewing.

items.title: Achyra affinitalis
items.content_text: Very common in grasslands

items.title: Castulo doubledayi
items.content_text: This moth was photographed on the eastern slopes of the Brisbane Ranges, at dusk.

items.title: Anthela varia
items.content_text: This is the larva of a member of the Anthelidea family and was photographed on the eastern slopes of the Brisbane Ranges, Victoria.

items.title: Orgyia anartoides
items.content_text: This is the larva form of a moth commonly known as the Painted Apple Moth.  It was photographed on the Eastern slopes of the Brisbane Ranges, Victoria

items.title: Pollanisus viridipulverulenta
items.content_text: This moth was making use of the nectar provided by the wildflower.
